<br>
I've seen this worked at alot in various methods by various guilds and I want to make a couple of points:<br>
<br>
(1)  The system is cumbersome and someone has to keep track.  Given our current track record on keeping track of things, this would be a serious burden to take up.<br>
<br>
(2)  No matter what you do, people will be miffed over loot distributions.<br>
<br>
(3)  Point systems tend to be heavily waited towards those that can play alot.  Given that we have a lot of players who are part time (at best), we'll end up with a stratified point system.<br>
<br>
(4)  No matter what you do, people will be miffed over loot distributions.<br>
<br>
(5)  Balancing a point system will take a ton of time.<br>
<br>
(6)  No matter what you do, people will be miffed over loot distributions.<br>
<br>
Given all of the above, I propose that we <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  do not</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> adopt a point system.<br>
<br>
Rather, I would rather us take up a system which is representative of how loot is distributed on most of the common group raid areas - the loot council.<br>
<br>
The loot council should consist of the group leaders and raid leader for the given raid.  Loot should be awarded on a &quot;need&quot; basis for affected characters and should only be awarded to characters present (not secondaries of players present).  If the council can't decide, then /random it.<br>
<br>
Also, if we're going to do this, we need to address cost.  High level spells have spell components which require lots of money to buy for a raid.  We need to adopt a system which renumerates casters for spell components, otherwise, they will bear the brunt of the cost while others gain the rewards.  Some raids cover this by splitting all gems amongst the casters only, we can look at this or other alternatives.<br>
<br>
Just food for thought...<br>
<br>
